---
import ContactCTA from '../components/ContactCTA.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About | Yuxuan Wang" description="About Yuxuan Wang — Data Scientist specializing in clinical NLP and production ML">
	<div class="stack gap-20">
		<main class="wrapper about">
			<Hero
				title="About"
				tagline="Thanks for stopping by. Read below to learn more about myself and my background."
			>
				<img
					width="1553"
					height="873"
					src="/assets/at-work.jpg"
					alt="Yuxuan Wang at work"
				/>
			</Hero>

			<section>
				<h2 class="section-title">Background</h2>
				<div class="content">
					<p>
						Machine learning engineer focused on clinical NLP and medical coding automation — building
						systems where model decisions carry real consequences and accuracy is measured in healthcare
						outcomes, not just benchmarks.
					</p>
					<p>
						At XpertDox, I work across the full stack: redesigning data infrastructure, training and
						owning production models, and translating performance into the business metrics that actually
						matter to clinical and product stakeholders. The scope has grown significantly — from a narrow
						ICD classifier to a platform covering CPT, ICD, and billing across 2,000 codes — and so has
						the responsibility to keep it reliable, scalable, and medically sound.
					</p>
					<p>
						Before this, I worked across media and healthcare during my M.S. at NYU — forecasting at
						NBCUniversal, predictive modeling for non-invasive glucose monitoring — building the range
						that makes domain-specific depth more useful. What I'm drawn to is work with staying power:
						problems where careful modeling, domain understanding, and engineering discipline create
						something that holds value as the tools around it continue to evolve.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>
			<section>
				<h2 class="section-title">How I Work</h2>
				<div class="content">
					<p>
						The longer I work in production ML, the more my definition of a good model has shifted —
						from one with strong metrics to one that actually fits the system it lives in and generates
						real value there. Those aren't always the same thing.
					</p>
					<p>
						In high-stakes domains, you can't just learn patterns and route decisions through the output.
						The most valuable uses of a model often aren't the obvious ones. Sometimes it's most useful
						not when it's confidently right, but when it quietly disagrees — flagging cases where learned
						patterns diverge from established rules and handing those off for expert review.
					</p>
					<p>
						The technical work of building a good model is one problem. Knowing what to do with it in a
						system built around human expertise is a different problem — and usually the more interesting one.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>
			<section>
				<h2 class="section-title">Outside Work</h2>
				<div class="content">
					<p>
						Hip-hop has held my attention for a long time — specifically the craft of it. Writing lyrics
						forces a kind of precision that's hard to find elsewhere: a complete idea, a distinct voice,
						and something worth saying, all compressed into a tight structure. What draws me most is
						hip-hop as a platform — the way it lets you say something real and get it across to people
						who might not have encountered that perspective otherwise.
					</p>
					<p>
						I watch a lot of NBA and play basketball regularly. Team sports have a particular dynamic
						that I find genuinely compelling — five people with different roles and capabilities,
						working toward something none of them could do alone. The combination of individual
						excellence and collective coordination, and the way trust has to be built in real time
						under pressure, is hard to replicate.
					</p>
					<p>
						Trading card games scratch a different itch: they sit at the intersection of favorite IPs
						and actual intellectual challenge. Deck-building is a design problem with constraints, and
						competitive play is applied game theory. The fact that it wraps all of that in something
						you genuinely care about makes it easy to go deep.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>
		</main>

		<ContactCTA />
	</div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
	.about {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 3.5rem;
	}

	img {
		margin-top: 1.5rem;
		border-radius: 1.5rem;
		box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);
	}

	section {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 0.5rem;
		color: var(--gray-200);
	}

	.section-title {
		grid-column-start: 1;
		font-size: var(--text-xl);
		color: var(--gray-0);
	}

	.content {
		grid-column: 2 / 4;
	}

	.content :global(a) {
		text-decoration: 1px solid underline transparent;
		text-underline-offset: 0.25em;
		transition: text-decoration-color var(--theme-transition);
	}

	.content :global(a:hover),
	.content :global(a:focus) {
		text-decoration-color: currentColor;
	}

	@media (min-width: 50em) {
		.about {
			display: grid;
			grid-template-columns: 1fr 60% 1fr;
		}

		.about > :global(:first-child) {
			grid-column-start: 2;
		}

		section {
			display: contents;
			font-size: var(--text-lg);
		}
	}
</style>
